Have we not here another example of a large class of prayers for knowledge for which there is no warrant in the life of Jesus? He knew what was in men, and was careful that his dis- ciples should have the same knowledge to the measure of their power. He set this wisdom on a level with harmless- ness, and indeed we know that it is the first requisite of harmlessness; for lack of it the truest hearts constantly involve the Church in shame and men in sorrow.
